## Architecture of deployed application (Ho, Rasmus)

The application was hosted using Microsoft’s Azure App Service

Our Application is hosted on the Azure app service. Here the client will connect to our Chirp.web application that handles the GUI Chirp.Infrastructure handles our database model as well as our repositories.

A User will connect to the Chirp.web application Interacting with the application. Chirp.web will then call Chirp.Infrastructure to store the data. If the user wants to log in through GitHub, Chirp.web will call GitHub authentication (OAuth), otherwise Chirp.Infrastructure will be called. This is used to create a user or retrieve credentials from a user in the database.  
![][image3]

### DB ER-Diagram

![][image4]  
(A Reaction requires the Author to have either a like or a dislike on the same Cheep)

When we made our first feature where Authors could follow each other, we made a non-critical error. In the Author entity we created a list of string, which stores the usernames of the Authors which the Author follows. However this creates a multi-valued attribute in the Author entity, which will decrease performance if an Author follows a lot of other Authors. This would especially be problematic when we began to query for Authors following a specific Author, since this would lead to querying through every Author instead of just doing it using a simple query.  
Instead we should have created a list of Authors, which would then have allowed EF Core to create a navigation property and create a relationship table instead.

# Process

## Build, test, release, and deployment

### Build and Test Workflow

| The workflow begins when a branch has been merged into the main. The workflow begins by attempting to first restore and then build the project. If the workflow is successful in doing this, it will then proceed to run the Unit, Integration and E2E tests.  For the E2E tests to work the application has to be running in the background. Other than that the workflow also has to install PlayWright Dependencies for them to work. Once all that is done, the E2E tests can finally run. If all the previous tests/checks passed, GitHub will then proceed to the Deploy to Azure Workflow. | ![][image7] |
| :---- | :---- |

### Deploy To Azure

| Once there has been a new merge to main, the workflow for deploying to Azure will begin. It starts by installing .NET 8, and then builds the application. It then uses ‘dotnet publish’ to create a self-contained deployment ready package. After that it will upload the necessary artifacts.  After all that, the workflow will begin to prepare for deployment. So it downloads the previously uploaded artifacts and proceeds to login to Azure using credentials given by repository GitHub secrets. It will then deploy the artifacts to Azure and the web app will now be fully online on Azure’s site.  | ![][image8] |
| :---- | :---- |

### Release Workflow

| The release workflow starts by retrieving the newest code from the repository, and also installs .NET 8\. The workflow then restores the application’s projects to make sure all dependencies have been installed, and then afterwards it will build the application. After that it will test all the tests, to make sure everything works as intended. Afterwards it will create the release name, and then it will run ‘dotnet publish’ to create a deployment ready package. At the end it will create the different ZIP releases for the different platforms, and then it creates the GitHub release itself with all the files.  | ![][image9] |
| :---- | :---- |

### Issue Adder Workflow

| When an issue has been opened, the issue adder workflow begins. It then executes the action called ‘add-to-project’ which then adds the issue itself to the project board. This is done to streamline creating issues. | ![][image10] |
| :---- | :---- |

## Teamwork

![][image11]

### Flow from creating issue to final implementation of a feature:

- Create the issue for the feature. Describe what is the reasoning for creating the feature, describe what the feature should do, and also give some acceptance criteria. Maybe the feature should be created in a certain way, or output a certain thing once done, etc.   
- Once the issue has been created, the issue automatically gets added to the project board. Here the issue can be placed into different categories: “Not Prioritized atm.”, “Todo”, “In Progress”, “Features for next Release” or “Done”. If the issue is mandatory/deemed necessary, it will be put into “Todo”. Otherwise, it will be put into “Not Prioritized atm.”.  
- Once a feature is being worked on, it will be put in “In Progress”. Then a new branch will be created for the feature work.   
- Once the work on the feature is done, and the work has been merged in through a pull request, the issue for the feature will be put into “Features For Next Release”. This category is used to know which features, bug fixes, or tests we have added since the last release.  
- Once a release has been created, the issues that were placed in “Features For Next Release” will be put into “Done” to signal that they are completed. 

### Tasks missing/incomplete:

- One thing that is not optimal is the helper methods created for the E2E tests. The idea behind the helper methods was to reduce redundant code. Since in a lot of tests it was required to create a user and then also log in with the user. Instead of having this code explicitly in each test that requires it, they were instead put into helper methods.   
  The problem is that the helper methods use the code generated by Playwright and not API calls to the functions specifically in the program. The reason why API calls would be a better choice is because, if the UI were to change in the future the helper methods would not have to be refactored to work, which is not the case at the moment.

## How to make Chirp\! work locally

1. First, you need to clone the repository using  
   git clone [https://github.com/ITU-BDSA2024-GROUP7/Chirp.git](https://github.com/ITU-BDSA2024-GROUP7/Chirp.git) 

2. .NET 8 is needed to run this application you can get it here:[https://dotnet.microsoft.com/en-us/download/dotnet/8.0](https://dotnet.microsoft.com/en-us/download/dotnet/8.0)   
     
     
3. Before running the app you have to set up GitHub secrets. This is for OAuth to work so that a user can register and login through GitHub (though it is also required for the normal program to work)  
     
   To set up GitHub secrets, first move into the Chirp.Web project ‘cd src\\Chirp.Web’  
     
   Afterwards create the metadata file necessary by writing:   
   ‘dotnet user-secrets init’  
     
   Then write and execute each following command separately:  
   ‘dotnet user-secrets set "authentication\_github\_clientId" "Ov23liFuhCLOJY4s2nRA"’  
     
   ‘dotnet user-secrets set "authentication\_github\_clientSecret" "32064af9ea476229907a38ef4bd92a15bc1e2778"’

   

4. Navigate to the directory of the repo called Chirp.Web and run the command ‘Dotnet watch’ to start the application

## How to run test suite locally

### Description of test suite

In the project, there are 3 types of tests: Unit tests, Integration tests, and E2E tests.  
Unit tests (Chirp.TestUnit) focus on specific functions in a very small and focused environment. These types of tests only focus on one specific function and make sure that they work without the involvement of other functions.

Integration tests (Chirp.TestIntegration) focus on specific endpoints, to make sure that the web app outputs the correct data. These focus on either the following list an author has or the cheeps on the web app.

E2E tests (Chirp.TestE2E) focus mainly on UI aspects of the web app. This can be everything from testing if the follow button works as intended, or if the user can write a cheep that has an image attached. These only focus on everything that the general user can do on Chirp. 

### How to be able to run the Playwright tests for the project:

If PowerShell is not installed

1. Run this command in CMD:

‘winget search Microsoft.PowerShell’   
	

2. Then execute the following command using bash  
   ‘winget install \--id Microsoft.PowerShell \--source winget’  
     
3. Afterwards locate PowerShell 7 (the pwsh.exe file) and set it as a PATH environment variable:

(Typically located here: C:\\Program Files\\PowerShell\\7\\pwsh.exe)

If/when Powershell has been installed:

1. Navigate to the Chirp.TestE2E project: ‘cd test\\Chirp.TestE2E’  
     
2. Afterwards run ‘dotnet build’ so that the Playwright installation file has been created  
     
3. Then execute the following command to install Playwright: ‘pwsh bin\\Debug\\net8.0\\playwright.ps1 install’

### 

### Running the tests

From this point you can move into the different test projects from the root:

- cd test\\Chirp.TestE2E  
- cd test\\Chirp.TestIntegration  
- cd test\\Chirp.TestUnit

Use ‘dotnet test’ in cmd to run the different tests. Important to note that the E2E tests are flaky when running all at the same time. The tests can run correctly by themselves, but when running all the tests some of the tests might fail. This is something that we looked into, but could not find the fix for it

To avoid this behavior we strongly suggest that you run an instance of the program in the background using ‘Dotnet watch’ in Chirp.web before running the ‘Dotnet Test’ Command in Chirp.TestE2E

## LLMs, ChatGPT, CoPilot, and others (Mathias)

**ChatGPT, CoPilot, and Claude**

ChatGPT, CoPilot, and Claude were used for.

- Troubleshooting and debugging  
- Code generation and auto-completions.

When writing code, we often found ourselves more confused by the use of LLMs. They were helpful to some degree in this aspect. The autocompletion feature helped increase coding productivity, but it often required tweaking because it didn’t always follow the same direction as we intended. For instance, when adding a link in the service layer to the repository, it would often autocomplete with the wrong method. In most cases, we found better answers by searching our issues on Google, which often redirected us to StackOverflow. The most helpful LLM was Copilot, as it could analyze the current files and gain context.

This was where the LLM excelled, as Copilot could acquire context and simplify trivial debugging scenarios. For more significant bugs, we referred to documentation, StackOverflow, and occasionally YouTube for clarity.  
ChatGPT was also beneficial in identifying the correct placement for dealing with warnings in the code and providing suggestions for fixes.

**CodeFactor**

During the initial weeks of the project and much of the development, we used CodeFactor for our pull requests. It often suggested minor formatting improvements, such as removing unnecessary spaces for clarity. Ultimately, we stopped using it because it started suggesting the removal of curly brackets and methods from the code, as it did not align with our preferences, we decided to discontinue its use.
